            desc: "Large irregular bone of pelvic girdle.<br><br><b>Ox Standard — formed by fusion of 3 bones at ACETABULUM:</b><br>- <b>Ilium</b> (cranial, largest)<br>- <b>Ischium</b> (caudal)<br>- <b>Pubis</b> (medial, ventral)<br><br><b>Important Palpable Landmarks:</b><br>- <b>Tuber Coxae</b> = HOOK BONE (cranial angle of ilium)<br>- <b>Tuber Sacrale</b> = top angle, near sacrum<br>- <b>Tuber Ischiadicum</b> = PIN BONE (caudal angle of ischium)<br><br><b>Other Features:</b><br>- <b>Acetabulum</b>: cup-shaped socket for head of femur (with acetabular notch & fossa).<br>- <b>Obturator Foramen</b>: large oval hole between pubis & ischium; transmits OBTURATOR NERVE.<br>- <b>Pelvic Symphysis</b>: midline fusion of right & left pubis + ischium.",
            eliteDesc: "<b>THE HIP BONE — OS COXAE</b><br><br>Each os coxae is a large flat-irregular bone made of 3 bones fused at the acetabulum:<br>• <b>Ilium</b> — wing-shaped, points cranially toward the sacrum.<br>• <b>Ischium</b> — caudal, forms the floor and back wall.<br>• <b>Pubis</b> — short, medial part forming the cranial floor.<br><br>The right & left os coxae meet ventrally at the <b>pelvic symphysis</b> and dorsally articulate with the sacrum at the <b>sacroiliac joint</b> — together they form the bony PELVIS (pelvic cavity = bony tunnel).<br><br><b>SURFACE LANDMARKS YOU CAN PALPATE on a live cow:</b><br>• <b>Tuber Coxae (Hook bone):</b> Cranio-lateral angle of the ilium; visible bump on the side of the rump. Used for body condition scoring.<br>• <b>Tuber Sacrale:</b> Dorso-medial angle close to the sacrum; the highest point of the rump.<br>• <b>Tuber Ischiadicum (Pin bone):</b> Caudal corner; sticks out on either side of the tail base.<br>The line joining hook → pin bones helps assess pelvic shape for calving ease.<br><br><b>ACETABULUM:</b> A deep cup formed by all 3 bones (ilium, ischium, pubis meet here). The smooth crescent <i>lunate surface</i> articulates with the head of the femur; the <i>acetabular fossa</i> is non-articular and gives attachment to the <i>round ligament</i>.<br><br><b>OBTURATOR FORAMEN:</b> The biggest hole in the body skeleton. Located between pubis & ischium. The obturator nerve and vessels exit here.<br><br><b>SEX DIFFERENCES:</b> In the cow, the pelvic inlet is wider & more rounded (for calving); in the bull it is narrower & more V-shaped.",
